@NODE "Bugs" "Known Bugs:"
@PREV "Main"

   There are currently no known bugs in these programs.  They do NOT write to
   your hard disk, so even if there were some bugs, your Hard disks should
   not suffer because of them (but this is NOT a @{" guarantee! " LINK "Warranty"}).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "TroubleShooting" "TroubleShooting:"
@PREV "Main"

   Currently, the helpfulness of these programs is somewhat limited since there
   is no way to write the data gathered by the Disk Helpers back to your
   Hard Disk.  Eventually, other programs will be written to do this, so that
   saved Hard Disk blocks can be restored to a known working condition.
   Sorry about that, but @{" I'm " LINK "Author"} just one guy!
    
   Either that or someone should port RDBSalvage.c, SCSIEd, or QuarterBack Tools to
   the AmigaOne & AmigaOS4!

   You can obtain device names & unit numbers from the @{B}Media ToolBox@{UB} program that comes
   with AmigaOS4, @{B}just DO NOT do any saving to disk, etc.@{UB}
   
   The information generated by @{" ReadHardBlocksPPC " LINK "ReadHardBlocksPPC"} should be saved or printed 
   out on paper for future use.  The only useful information will be in the 
   first block & all the partition blocks (unless you can figure out what the BOOT blocks
   contain!).
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE "RDBInformerPPC" "RDBInformerPPC Usage:"
@PREV "Main"

  @{FG SHINE} NAME @{FG TEXT}
      RDBInformerPPC
     
  @{FG SHINE} DESCRIPTION @{FG TEXT}
      This program will generate a textual output that describes the Hard Disk
      you specify with deviceName & unitNumber.
      
  @{FG SHINE} SYNOPSIS @{FG TEXT}
      RDBInformerPPC deviceName unitNumber [>outputFile]

  @{FG SHINE} EXAMPLE @{FG TEXT}
      > RDBInformerPPC scsi.device    4 >RAM:ScsiDev4.output
      > RDBInformerPPC gvpscsi.device 6
      > RDBInformerPPC a1ide.device   2 >RAM:Dev2.output 

  @{FG SHINE} AUTHOR @{FG TEXT}
      @{" The Author of the original RDBInformer " LINK "ForeignAuthors"}

  @{FG SHINE} SEE ALSO @{FG TEXT}
      @{" ReadHardBlocksPPC   " LINK "ReadHardBlocksPPC"}
      @{" Read Source Code    " SYSTEM "Sys:Utilities/Multiview RDBInformer.c"}
      @{" Read Example Output " SYSTEM "Sys:Utilities/Multiview RDBInformer.output"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CheckForSCSI" "CheckForSCSI (example script file):"

   This is the contents of the CheckForSCSI script file: @{FG SHINE}
   
      .key ENVVAR/A,VOLUMENAME/A
      .bra {
      .ket }

      FailAt 21

      CheckSCSIVolPPC {ENVVAR} {VOLUMENAME}

      If WARN ; RETURN_WARN came from CheckSCSIVolPPC
         echo {ENVVAR} "is" {VOLUMENAME}
      Else
         echo {ENVVAR} "is NOT" {VOLUMENAME}
      Endif @{FG TEXT}
	
   All it does is check that a given ENVVAR contains VOLUMENAME.  If the
   test is true, @{" CheckSCSIVolPPC " LINK "CheckSCSIVolPPC"} will return RETURN_WARN = 5, or else
   @{" CheckSCSIVolPPC " LINK "CheckSCSIVolPPC"} will either return RETURN_ERROR or RETURN_FAIL.
   (You do know how to run script files don't you?)
   
@ENDNODE

@NODE "CheckSCSIVolPPC" "CheckSCSIVolPPC Usage:"

  @{FG SHINE} NAME @{FG TEXT}
     CheckSCSIVolPPC
     
  @{FG SHINE} DESCRIPTION @{FG TEXT}
     Read a SCSI Environment string & determine if the given volume is part
     of the environment variable.  The name of each environmental
     variable written by our companion program @{" SetSCSIEnvPPC " LINK "SetSCSIEnvPPC"} is as follows: @{FG SHINE}

       SCSIENV_10 @{FG TEXT}(which is SCSI (UnitNumber - 1) * 10 + LUN = 10)

     Each Environmental variable is written to ENVARC: AND ENV: by @{" SetSCSIEnvPPC " LINK "SetSCSIEnvPPC"}

     If you examine the @{" sample script " LINK "CheckForSCSI"}, you can see that you can use @{" SetSCSIEnvPPC " LINK "SetSCSIEnvPPC"} & this program
     to check for the existence & location of volumes that might be removable.  The original
     use @{" I " LINK "Author"} had for these programs involved Magneto-Optical disk drives that had removable
     media.
            
  @{FG SHINE} SYNOPSIS @{FG TEXT}
     int rval = CheckSCSIVolPPC envVariableName volumeName

  @{FG SHINE} RETURNS @{FG TEXT}
      5 (RETURN_WARN) if the volume name is part of the environment string.
     10 (RETURN_ERROR) or 20 (RETURN_FAIL) otherwise.

  @{FG SHINE} AUTHOR @{FG TEXT}
     @{" That's me! " LINK "Author"}

  @{FG SHINE} COPYRIGHT @{FG TEXT}
     Copyright (C) 1996-2004 by J.T. Steichen, All rights reserved.

  @{FG SHINE} HISTORY @{FG TEXT}
     16-Nov-2004 - Ported to AmigaOS4 & gcc.
     21-Mar-1996 - Created.

  @{FG SHINE} SEE ALSO @{FG TEXT}
      @{" SetSCSIEnvPPC       " LINK "SetSCSIEnvPPC"}
      @{" Read Source Code    " SYSTEM "Sys:Utilities/Multiview CheckSCSIVol.c"}
      @{" Read Example Script " LINK "CheckForSCSI"} -- CheckForSCSI script file

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SetSCSIEnvPPC" "SetSCSIEnvPPC Usage:"
   
  @{FG SHINE} NAME @{FG TEXT}
      SetSCSIEnvPPC
      
  @{FG SHINE} DESCRIPTION @{FG TEXT}
     Read all logical units on the given deviceName & make Environment strings from
     all partition names found in the Rigid Disk Block's information.
     The original use @{" I " LINK "Author"} had for these programs involved Magneto-Optical disk 
     drives that had removable media.

  @{FG SHINE} SYNOPSIS @{FG TEXT}
     SetSCSIEnvPPC deviceName
     
  @{FG SHINE} EXAMPLE @{FG TEXT}
      > SetSCSIEnv scsi.device
      > SetSCSIEnv gvpscsi.device
      > SetSCSIEnv a1ide.device

